detail.content: Special Relativity Animations        Movies Demonstrating Special Relativity   Except for the first two movies below, the movies on this page demonstrate various effects of special relativity.      Choose a Topic:          Measuring the Speed Through the Ether This shows  how one could determine one's velocity relative to a medium through  which waves travel.        Simultaneity This demonstrates that two events,  simultaneous as observed from one inertial frame of reference are not  simultaneous when observed from another inertial frame.        Time Dilation This demonstrates that "moving  clocks" advance more slowly than stationary clocks.          Measuring the Speed of Light (Galilean Relativity)   This shows that in Galilean relativity, two observers moving relative  to each other will measure different values for the speed of light.        Everyone Measures the Same Speed of Light in Special Relativity  This demonstrates how two  observers moving relative to each other measure the same speed of light.       Moving Clocks  This demonstrates how each of two  observers, moving relative to each other, sees the other observer's  clocks as running slow.         Points in Euclidean space view from Unprimed and Primed (rotated)  Frame  This demonstrates how the coordinates of a  set of points in the x-y plane depend on the coordinate system from  which they are viewed.         Space-Time Diagrams of Events in Primed and Unprimed Frames Showing  Grid  This demonstrates how the coordinates of a  set of events in space-time depend on the inertial frame  (coordinate system) from which they are viewed.        Space-Time Diagrams of Events in Primed and Unprimed Frames (no grid)    This is the same as the previous item, but no grid lines are shown.       Return to Animation Studies
